## ‚úÖ What Happens If You **DON‚ÄôT** Pass a Dependency Array?

### ‚úÖ Behaviour

> **The effect runs after EVERY render (initial render + every re-render).**

That means:

*   Initial render ‚úÖ
*   Any state change ‚úÖ
*   Any prop change ‚úÖ
*   Parent re-render ‚úÖ

***

## ‚úÖ Simple Example

```jsx
function App() {
  const [count, setCount] = React.useState(0);

  useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Effect ran");
  });

  return (
    <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
      Count: {count}
    </button>
  );
}
```

### ‚úÖ Output

    Effect ran   // initial render
    Effect ran   // count = 1
    Effect ran   // count = 2
    Effect ran   // count = 3
    ...

‚û°Ô∏è **Runs on every render**

***

## ‚úÖ Why React Does This

When you omit the dependency array:

*   React **assumes the effect depends on everything**
*   So it re-runs the effect every time the component renders

This mirrors **class component behavior**:

```js
componentDidUpdate() {
  // runs after every update
}
```

***

## ‚ùå Common Problem (Infinite Loop)

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  setCount(count + 1);
});
```

üí• This causes an **infinite render loop**

### Why?

1.  Component renders
2.  `useEffect` runs
3.  `setCount` triggers re-render
4.  Effect runs again
5.  Repeat forever ‚ùå

***

## ‚úÖ Visual Comparison (VERY IMPORTANT)

| useEffect Syntax              | When it Runs            |
| ----------------------------- | ----------------------- |
| `useEffect(() => {})`         | After **every render**  |
| `useEffect(() => {}, [])`     | **Once** (on mount)     |
| `useEffect(() => {}, [a, b])` | When `a` or `b` changes |

***

## ‚úÖ When Is It OK to Omit Dependency Array?

‚úÖ Rare cases:

*   Logging renders
*   Measuring DOM after each render
*   Syncing non-React code every render

### Example (safe)

```js
useEffect(() => {
  console.log("Component rendered");
});
```

***

## ‚ùå When It Is a Bad Idea

‚ùå API calls  
‚ùå Event listeners  
‚ùå Timers (`setInterval`, `setTimeout`)  
‚ùå Subscriptions

Example ‚ùå:

```js
useEffect(() => {
  fetchData(); // ‚ùå will run on every render
});
```

***

## ‚úÖ Correct Usage for Common Scenarios

### ‚úÖ Run Once (on mount)

```js
useEffect(() => {
  fetchData();
}, []);
```

***

### ‚úÖ Run when value changes

```js
useEffect(() => {
  fetchData(query);
}, [query]);
```

***

### ‚úÖ With cleanup (important!)

```js
useEffect(() => {
  const id = setInterval(() => console.log("tick"), 1000);

  return () => clearInterval(id);
}, []);
```

***

## ‚úÖ Interview‚ÄëReady Answer ‚≠ê

> **If no dependency array is provided, `useEffect` runs after every render of the component. This can cause performance issues or infinite loops if state is updated inside the effect.**

***

## ‚úÖ One‚ÄëLine Version (Most Asked)

**‚Äú`useEffect` without dependencies runs after every render.‚Äù**

***

## ‚úÖ Golden Rule to Remember üßÝ

    No dependency array ‚Üí runs always
